								and templated with <a class="http://twig.sensiolabs.org/">Twig</a>. With <a href="https://github.com/kzykhys/Ciconia">Ciconia</a> it additionally supports Markdown & a few other custom parsers I've written along the way.
								Comments are annoying to implement; realistically you need users to log in to prevent spam. That's why I just shrugged and used <a class="">Disqus</a> ;).
								It initially sported an all-on-site editor, but after swapping to <a href="http://purecss.io/">Pure CSS</a> from Bootstrap,
								I instead implemented <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/XML-RPC_Support">WordPress's XMLRPC API</a>.
								Just like WordPress, the API gracefully degrades features for older blogging standards.
							<p>
								In layman's terms desktop applications, mobile apps and web tools that support
								WordPress's XMLRPC will work with it, such as <a href="http://openlivewriter.org/"><strike>Windows</strike> Open Live Writer</a>.
							</p>
